title: For Sale:  Colt Lightening Rifle Medium Frame .32-20 Made in 1889
postcontent: Up for sale is my Colt Lightening Rifle serial number 39,XXX built in 1889  .  I bought this in early 2003 at Ruff's Guns and Liquor (They have since changed the name to Ruff's Guns, I loved it that they sold both guns and liquor in the same shop!) in Flagstaff, AZ.  I was told at time of purchase that it had come from a local estate sale and that is all I was told about it.  I was pretty excited when I found it and bought it for use in cowboy action shooting  (It was fun to see the looks on the faces of people at the shoots that I had a real vintage Colt Lightening and was shooting it in competition and not a reproduction.)  It is a medium frame model and is in .32-20 caliber, which is a pleasure to load and shoot.  It has a 21 inch octogon barrel and the curved steel butt plate.  This rifle does have some issues that I want any potential buyers to be aware of.  First, the bore quaility is poor.  It is worn and the bore is slightly pitted and it leads up quickly.  It worked fine for close up cowboy targets, but at longer ranges its accuracy was poor.  Second, the stock is cracked where it meets the rear of the reciever.  It has had what looked like a poorly done old repair that is holding, but not very good.  Third, is the finish.  The outside of this rifle looks as if it had been in a scabbard its whole working life, and it does look like it was a working ranch rifle by the marks and dings it has.  Its best atribute is that the action is solid!  I took it completely apart and did a detailed cleaning and inspection when I bought it and the inside is great.  The action is crisp and solid with no slop what so ever.  The springs have good strength and it loads and fires as it should.  I had planned on replacing the wood, having the barrel sleeved but I ended up finding another Lightening in .38-40 that I now use.  Feel free to contact me about any questions you have about the rifle. I tried to place more pictures of the rifle on this listing, but they were too large and I couldn't put them on here.  So if you need more pictures I can email them to you.

title: For Sale:  KEL-TEC KSG SHOTGUN NIB
postcontent:
We  purchased this several months ago, it has been out of the box to look at have but never fired.  

This is a brand new, never been fired Kel-Tec KSG bullpup 12-gauge pump action shotgun designed by Kel-Tec.   The KSG ejects casings downward rather than forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 pounds and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1-inch overall length and an 18.5-inch cylinder bore barrel.

The internal dual tube magazines hold 14 rounds of 12 gauge 2-3/4-inch shotshells (7 per tube). The pump action feeds from either the left or right tube.
 Each tube holds a total of seven 2.75 in (70 mm) 12-gauge shotshells or six 3 in (76 mm) shotshells.

The Kel-Tec KSG shotgun is a manually operated, pump (slide) action weapon. Barrel locking is achieved by a swinging wedge, located inside the top of the bolt, which engages the barrel extension. The sliding forend is connected to the bolt by dual operating bars. The ammunition feed is from two independent tubular magazines, located below the barrel.

The user is required to manually select a magazine by switching a three-position lever, located behind the pistol grip. The middle position of the switch blocks the feed from both magazines and allows the user to chamber a single round manually. Switching the lever to one side brings the respective magazine into the feed cycle. Once one magazine is depleted, the user manually switches to the second magazine by pushing the magazine selection lever toward it.[2]

Rounds are loaded into the magazines through a large loading/ejection port, located at the bottom of the gun in the stock, behind the pistol grip. Empty shells are ejected down through the same port. A manual safety is available in the form of the cross-bolt button, located above the grip, making the gun fully ambidextrous in use. Sighting equipment (iron sights and/or red dot sights) can be installed using the standard Picatinny rail located above the barrel. An second Picatinny rail is provided at the bottom of the sliding forend, permitting installation of other Picatinny rail accessories. While not included with the stock weapon, perpendicular forward grips and back-up iron sights (BUIS) are almost always shown in photography and video demonstrations of the Kel-Tec KSG
